id: pm-7hye
title: "ADR: adopt \"repository-native project context engine\" as the product category; pm as master brand over CLI/MCP/SDK/Web/Packages surfaces (proposed)"
description: "Human-gated positioning decision. Ratifies the three-level category system (agent-native project management as searchable category, repository-native project context engine as differentiated category, context infrastructure as vision), the pm master brand with named surfaces, the doctrine line, and the exact public metadata copy — before any public copy changes ship."
type: Decision
status: open
priority: 1
tags[3]: adr,marketing,positioning
created_at: "2026-07-13T09:29:47.229Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-13T09:30:08.719Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 90
acceptance_criteria: "Maintainer explicitly accepts or amends the category statement, brand architecture, doctrine, and metadata copy; rejected alternative categories recorded; acceptance unblocks the Phase-1 message-surface rewrite"
parent: pm-wjfa
risk: medium
confidence: high
body: "# ADR: product category and brand architecture (proposed)\n\n## Context\nCurrent public descriptor \"Git-native project management CLI for humans and agents\" compresses the product into a crowded category (Markdown task trackers, terminal Kanban) and hides the strongest capabilities: explainable context ranking, durable plans, evidence graph, replayable history, typed SDK, MCP/skills surfaces, context-quality evaluation. Repo shows 1300+ commits and dozens of releases against single-digit stars — a positioning/distribution/proof gap, not a feature gap. The master brand is currently perceived as \"pm-cli\" (an interface), while the product spans CLI, SDK, MCP, plugins, Web, packages, search adapters, profiles, and an evaluation framework.\n\n## Decision (proposed)\n1. Category statement: **\"pm is the repository-native project context engine for coding agents and software teams.\"** Supporting: \"It turns work into compact, queryable, auditable context: ranked next actions, durable plans, dependencies, decisions, evidence, and history — stored in Git and available through CLI, MCP, TypeScript SDK, and Web.\"\n2. Three-level category system: familiar/searchable = \"agent-native project management\" (SEO + comparison pages only); differentiated = \"repository-native project context engine\"; vision = \"context infrastructure for software work\".\n3. Doctrine: \"Project management is context management.\" Promise: \"Give every coding agent the right project context.\" Campaign: \"Your coding agent can write code. pm tells it what matters.\"\n4. Master brand = **pm**; surfaces named pm CLI / pm MCP / pm SDK / pm Web / pm Packages. Technical identifiers (unbraind/pm-cli, @unbrained/pm-cli, pm, pm-mcp, /sdk subpaths) unchanged — no rename.\n5. Exact metadata copy (GitHub About, npm description, website title/meta, social card, topics/keywords) as recorded in note (5) on parent pm-wjfa.\n\n## Rejected alternatives (do not relitigate)\n- \"AI project manager\" — implies autonomous personality, not dependable infrastructure.\n- \"Agent memory\" — Beads occupies it; understates workflow, evidence, governance.\n- \"Task tracker for AI\" — undersells the system.\n- \"MCP project manager\" — ties identity to one transport.\n- \"Context OS\" — too grand before the category exists.\n- \"AI-powered project management\" — generic; falsely implies model dependence.\n- \"CLI-first Jira replacement\" — frames around incumbents instead of the agent problem.\n- Renaming the package/binary — destroys compatibility and search equity for no positioning gain.\n\n## Consequences\n- Phase-1 message-surface rewrite (README/website/About/npm/topics) is blocked on this acceptance; drift-reconciliation and agent-distribution work is NOT (correctness ships regardless).\n- \"Why context engine\": the system stores, selects/ranks, delivers, updates, and evaluates context, and preserves continuity — \"project\" keeps it concrete vs generic RAG; \"repository-native\" carries local-first, reviewable, portable, no mandatory backend.\n- All public counts (commands/tools/capabilities/packages) become generated from contracts/catalog, never hand-written, so the category claim is never undermined by drift."
